         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ [An eloquent speech was made by Dr. Mueller, who read some verses which he had received from Mr. W. Stitt Jenkins, on the fate of Leichardt. ¶ ]...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">65.02.00a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Stitt Jenkins</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. For the text given here, see the report of the St David's Day dinner in Melbourne, 1 March 1865 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus, </seg>2 March 1865, p. 5). </p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[An eloquent speech was made by Dr. Mueller, who read some verses which he had received from Mr. W. Stitt Jenkins, on the fate of Leichardt.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Error for Leichhardt. Verses not found. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Melbourne Punch</seg>, 9 March 1865, p. 2 in <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'Recognition of real genius' commented:</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.5in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="">DR</seg>. <seg style="">MUELLER</seg> appears to have just found out what Mr. PUNCH discovered years ago—the greatness of Geelong's lyric poet. The doctor describes Mr. <seg style="">STITT</seg> JENKINS "as a truly great man—a person of noble mind, and one whose poetry he compares with that of SCHILLER." Surely, after this, Geelong must give its poet a statue, and send for <seg style="">MUELLER</seg> to inaugurate it. With regard to the comparison, it is no doubt a just one, as many persons have likened Geelongese to German.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Jenkins responded in a letter to the Editor of the<seg style="font-style: italic; "> Age, </seg>14 March 1865, p. 7, ending it with:</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.5118in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">Having long borne, as best I might, the yelping of curs and snarls of souls debased, it was with heart felt gratitude that I read the kind things the good doctor was pleased to say of verses of which none better than myself know the ruggedness. And, although his face I have never seen, and peradventure never may, the knowledge that I have been deemed worthy of the friendship of a man so worthily world-renowned, will enable me to bear up against the trials Providence may still have in store for me, and so enduring until the grave shall shut me out from earthly cares for ever. Yet do I feel that after death justice will be done me, and that my name will live in the grateful remembrance of millions when that of</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 1.0437in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">Mr <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Punch</seg>, and all his worthless kin,</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 1.0437in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">Are buried dark and deep</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 1.0437in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">The earth's great womb within.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.8465in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">And in such assurance of hope, I remain, Sir,</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.8465in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">Your faithful servant,</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.8465in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">W. STITT JENKINS</p>
                  <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
               </note>]</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
